channel.description:
I know help for this topic has been posted a million times, but none seem to clarify my problem.
When I open compile.bat it says this;
'You do not have Java installed. Please download it at the site that is about to load.'
Then it loads Java.com and expects me to download the newest one, I've downloaded it and changed the environmental variables to 07 more than once, yet it still doesn't work.
Please help. I downloaded the newest Java, supposedly. It's the 79mb one (jdk-6u7-windows-i586-p.exe). [br][br][size=1]Posted on: September 19, 2008, 05:13:18 pm[/size][hr]Nobody's gonna help? :(

item.title: Compiler issues
item.dc:creator: @Hawt Hawt
item.description:
@Hawt wrote:

Oh okay.[br][br][size=1]Posted on: September 19, 2008, 05:47:27 pm[/size][hr]@echo off
if exist “%programfiles%\Java” (call :compile “%programfiles%\Java”) else (goto error)
:compile
for /D %%x in ("%~1jdk*") do (set p="%%~x\bin\javac.exe")
if defined p (%p% -cp . *.java)
if defined p (goto end)
:error
echo You do not have Java installed. Please download it at the site that is about to load.
“%programfiles%\Internet Explorer\iexplore.exe” http://java.sun.com/javase/downloads/index.jsp
:end
echo Finished!
pause
exit[br][br][size=1]Posted on: September 19, 2008, 05:59:09 pm[/size][hr]what now?

item.title: Compiler issues
item.dc:creator: @Project_Evolution Project Evolution
item.description:
@Project_Evolution wrote:

~How to Compile~

First off, after finishing editing a .java file or any file in your server. Save it. Then find your Compiler, it should be in there as a .bat file, and open it. Then press C and then press Enter. Your compiler should say somethings or just simply, “Files compiled successfully!”

Once it says that, it mean’s you have compiled your source/server. Press Enter and you will either exit or return to your compiler’s menu.

~How to Fix the Error~

I cant fix your compiler since I dont know the code that made it. Here’s how you can show me;

Right-Click > Edit > Copy and Paste the code shown in the text file.
